      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I was just using the goblin analogy to illustrate the idea of a small, persistent disturbance. Let's dive into the technical aspects of the beating effect.\n\nThe beating effect occurs when two frequencies that are close together, but not identical, are perceived by the auditory system. When a minor second, like C to C#, is played, the two frequencies (C and C#) are about 9:10 apart, which means the frequency of the C# is about 9/10 times the frequency of the C.\n\nAs the two frequencies oscillate, they create an interference pattern in the auditory system. The interference pattern is like a series of constructive and destructive interference zones, where the sound waves either reinforce or cancel each other out. The beating effect is caused by the constructive interference zones, where the sound waves reinforce each other, creating a pulsating or wavering sensation.\n\nThe auditory nerve processes the interference pattern by detecting the difference in frequencies between the two sounds. This difference in frequencies is perceived as a pitch difference, which is why the minor second sounds dissonant. The brain is essentially trying to reconcile the two frequencies, which can create a sense of tension or instability.\n\nTo illustrate this, imagine a goblin trying to balance a sees",
